WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.725 --> 00:00:16.345
Eric Hirshberg: So I assume that Norman doesn't need much of an introduction,
艾瑞克·利德尔：我想大家都很熟悉诺曼了，不需要太多的介绍，

2
00:00:16.369 --> 00:00:17.874
but TED's audience is global,
但是TED的观众来自全球，

3
00:00:17.898 --> 00:00:19.095
it's diverse,
是个多元的群体，

4
00:00:19.119 --> 00:00:22.105
so I've been tasked with starting with his bio,
所以我被要求从介绍他的生平开始，

5
00:00:22.129 --> 00:00:24.415
which could easily take up the entire 18 minutes.
这轻易就能用完整个18分钟。

6
00:00:24.439 --> 00:00:28.382
So instead we're going to do 93 years in 93 seconds or less.
所以我们决定用93秒或更少的时间来介绍诺曼的这93年。

7
00:00:28.406 --> 00:00:29.556
(Laughter)
（笑声）

8
00:00:30.078 --> 00:00:31.625
You were born in New Hampshire.
你生于新罕布什尔州。

9
00:00:31.649 --> 00:00:33.364
Norman Lear: New Haven, Connecticut.
诺曼·李尔：是纽黑文，康涅狄格州。

10
00:00:33.388 --> 00:00:34.674
EH: New Haven, Connecticut.
艾瑞克：是纽黑文，康涅狄格州。

11
00:00:34.698 --> 00:00:37.586
(Laughter)
（笑声）

12
00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:39.230
NL: There goes seven more seconds.
诺曼：这就过去7秒了。

13
00:00:39.254 --> 00:00:40.497
EH: Nailed it.
艾瑞克：你做到了。

14
00:00:40.521 --> 00:00:42.511
(Laughter)
（笑声）

15
00:00:42.862 --> 00:00:44.767
You were born in New Haven, Connecticut.
你生于纽黑文，康涅狄格州。

16
00:00:44.791 --> 00:00:47.196
Your father was a con man -- I got that right.
你的父亲是个行骗者——这次我对了。

17
00:00:47.220 --> 00:00:49.967
He was taken away to prison when you were nine years old.
在你九岁的时候他被带走去了监狱。

18
00:00:49.991 --> 00:00:53.148
You flew 52 missions as a fighter pilot in World War II.
在二战中你是一位飞行员执行了52次任务。

19
00:00:53.506 --> 00:00:54.656
You came back to --
你回到——

20
00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:55.830
NL: Radio operator.
诺曼：是报务员。

21
00:00:56.362 --> 00:00:58.845
EH: You came to LA to break into Hollywood,
艾瑞克：你来到洛杉矶闯入了好莱坞，

22
00:00:58.869 --> 00:01:00.749
first in publicity, then in TV.
首先当宣传，接着是在电视领域。

23
00:01:00.773 --> 00:01:02.932
You had no training as a writer, formally,
你是一位没有接受过正式训练的作家，

24
00:01:02.956 --> 00:01:04.360
but you hustled your way in.
但你闯出了你的路。

25
00:01:04.384 --> 00:01:05.837
Your breakthrough, your debut,
你的突破，你的首秀，

26
00:01:05.861 --> 00:01:08.129
was a little show called "All in the Family."
是一部电视剧《全家福》。

27
00:01:08.153 --> 00:01:10.257
You followed that up with a string of hits
紧接着你拍了一系列

28
00:01:10.281 --> 00:01:12.399
that to this day is unmatched in Hollywood:
至今都在好莱坞无与伦比的电视剧：

29
00:01:12.423 --> 00:01:14.463
"Sanford and Son," "Maude," "Good Times,"
《桑福德和儿子》，《Maude》，《好时光》，

30
00:01:14.487 --> 00:01:16.313
"The Jeffersons," "One Day at a Time,"
《杰佛逊一家》，《随遇而安》，

31
00:01:16.337 --> 00:01:17.750
"Mary Hartman, Mary Hartman,"
《玛丽·哈特曼》，

32
00:01:17.774 --> 00:01:19.537
to name literally a fraction of them.
这里只提到了一部分。

33
00:01:19.561 --> 00:01:21.338
Not only are they all commercially --
这些电视剧不仅在商业上——

34
00:01:21.362 --> 00:01:25.368
(Applause)
（掌声）

35
00:01:25.392 --> 00:01:28.377
Not only are they all commercially successful,
它们不仅都获得了商业上的成功，

36
00:01:28.401 --> 00:01:30.375
but many of them push our culture forward
其中很多电视剧也推动了文化的发展，

37
00:01:30.399 --> 00:01:32.761
by giving the underrepresented members of society
让社会中代表性不足的群体

38
00:01:32.785 --> 00:01:34.821
their first prime-time voice.
首次在黄金时段发声。

39
00:01:35.153 --> 00:01:38.464
You have seven shows in the top 10 at one time.
你曾有七部电视剧同时在收视率前十。

40
00:01:38.853 --> 00:01:40.082
At one point,
你一度吸引了

41
00:01:40.106 --> 00:01:43.443
you aggregate an audience of 120 million people per week
一亿两千万的的观众

42
00:01:43.467 --> 00:01:44.693
watching your content.
每周观看你的电视剧。

43
00:01:44.717 --> 00:01:46.956
That's more than the audience for Super Bowl 50,
这甚至超过了每年一度的超级杯

44
00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:48.219
which happens once a year.
在2015年的观众数。

45
00:01:48.243 --> 00:01:49.465
NL: Holy shit.
诺曼：哇靠。

46
00:01:49.489 --> 00:01:51.262
(Laughter)
（笑声）

47
00:01:51.286 --> 00:01:53.508
(Applause)
（掌声）

48
00:01:53.532 --> 00:01:55.891
EH: And we're not even to the holy shit part.
艾瑞克：我们甚至还没有说到令人惊叹的哇靠部分。

49
00:01:55.915 --> 00:01:56.954
(Laughter)
（笑声）

50
00:01:56.978 --> 00:01:59.705
You land yourself on Richard Nixon's enemies list --
你使自己成为理查德·尼克松名单上的敌人——

51
00:01:59.729 --> 00:02:00.879
he had one.
他有这么一份。

52
00:02:01.219 --> 00:02:03.314
That's an applause line, too.
这也值得大家的掌声。

53
00:02:03.338 --> 00:02:05.140
(Applause)
（掌声）

54
00:02:05.164 --> 00:02:08.761
You're inducted into the TV Hall of Fame on the first day that it exists.
你在名单曝光第一天就被列入了电视名人堂。

55
00:02:08.785 --> 00:02:10.185
Then came the movies.
接下来说说电影。

56
00:02:10.209 --> 00:02:11.789
"Fried Green Tomatoes,"
《油炸绿蕃茄》，

57
00:02:11.813 --> 00:02:13.838
"The Princess Bride," "Stand By Me,"
《公主新娘》，《伴我同行》，

58
00:02:13.862 --> 00:02:15.035
"This Is Spinal Tap."
《摇滚万岁》。

59
00:02:15.059 --> 00:02:16.196
(Applause)
（掌声）

60
00:02:16.220 --> 00:02:17.752
Again, just to name a fraction.
这里还是只提了一部分。

61
00:02:17.776 --> 00:02:18.807
(Applause)
（掌声）

62
00:02:18.831 --> 00:02:20.337
Then you wipe the slate clean,
然后你开创了"三幕剧架构" 横扫了电影界，

63
00:02:20.361 --> 00:02:24.408
start a third act as a political activist focusing on protecting the First Amendment
从政时致力于保护第一修正案，

64
00:02:24.432 --> 00:02:26.382
and the separation of church and state.
坚持政教分离。

65
00:02:26.406 --> 00:02:28.296
You start People For The American Way.
你建立了美国之道团体。

66
00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:30.178
You buy the Declaration of Independence
你买下了独立宣言，

67
00:02:30.202 --> 00:02:31.693
and give it back to the people.
然后把它归还给人民。

68
00:02:31.717 --> 00:02:34.055
You stay active in both entertainment and politics
你到93岁高龄

69
00:02:33.269 --> 00:02:35.611
until the ripe old of age of 93,
都还一直活跃在娱乐界和政界，

70
00:02:35.635 --> 00:02:36.881
when you write a book
然后你开始写书，

71
00:02:36.905 --> 00:02:39.069
and make a documentary about your life story.
并且制作了一部关于你人生的纪录片。

72
00:02:39.093 --> 00:02:40.267
And after all that,
经过了所有这些，

73
00:02:40.291 --> 00:02:42.833
they finally think you're ready for a TED Talk.
他们终于觉得你准备好做一个TED演讲了。

74
00:02:42.857 --> 00:02:44.638
(Laughter)
（笑声）

75
00:02:44.662 --> 00:02:49.234
(Applause)
（掌声）

76
00:02:49.258 --> 00:02:51.056
NL: I love being here.
诺曼：很高兴来到这里。

77
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.795
And I love you for agreeing to do this.
也很高兴你同意做这个访谈。

78
00:02:53.819 --> 00:02:55.808
EH: Thank you for asking. It's my honor.
艾瑞克：谢谢你的邀请。我的荣幸。

79
00:02:55.832 --> 00:02:57.379
So here's my first question.
然后这是我的第一个问题。

80
00:02:57.739 --> 00:02:59.453
Was your mother proud of you?
你的妈妈为你感到骄傲吗？

81
00:02:59.477 --> 00:03:01.473
(Laughter)
（笑声）

82
00:03:01.875 --> 00:03:03.208
NL: My mother ...
诺曼：我的妈妈……

83
00:03:03.232 --> 00:03:04.399
what a place to start.
从这里开始啊。

84
00:03:06.787 --> 00:03:08.938
Let me put it this way --
让我这样说吧——

85
00:03:08.962 --> 00:03:10.582
when I came back from the war,
当我从战场上回来，

86
00:03:10.606 --> 00:03:16.194
she showed me the letters that I had written her from overseas,
她给我看了我从海外寄给她的信，

87
00:03:16.218 --> 00:03:18.615
and they were absolute love letters.
这些绝对都是情书。

88
00:03:21.781 --> 00:03:23.360
(Laughter)
（笑声）

89
00:03:23.384 --> 00:03:25.106
This really sums up my mother.
这确实概括形容了我妈妈。

90
00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:26.701
They were love letters,
那些情书，

91
00:03:26.725 --> 00:03:28.927
as if I had written them to --
仿佛我把它们写成那样一般——

92
00:03:28.951 --> 00:03:30.248
they were love letters.
它们就是情书。

93
00:03:33.034 --> 00:03:37.567
A year later I asked my mother if I could have them,
一年后我问妈妈，我是否能拥有它们，

94
00:03:37.591 --> 00:03:41.868
because I'd like to keep them all the years of my life ...
因为我想保存它们一生……

95
00:03:41.892 --> 00:03:43.401
She had thrown them away.
她已经扔掉了。

96
00:03:43.425 --> 00:03:47.488
(Laughter)
（笑声）

97
00:03:48.710 --> 00:03:50.014
That's my mother.
这就是我妈妈。

98
00:03:50.038 --> 00:03:52.516
(Laughter)
（笑声）

99
00:03:52.540 --> 00:03:59.060
The best way I can sum it up in more recent times is --
近期，我能总结的最好方式——

100
00:03:59.084 --> 00:04:01.381
this is also more recent times --
这也是最近的事——

101
00:04:01.405 --> 00:04:02.587
a number of years ago,
几年前，

102
00:04:02.611 --> 00:04:06.484
when they started the Hall of Fame to which you referred.
当他们开始筹备你刚刚提到的名人堂的时候。

103
00:04:06.508 --> 00:04:08.291
It was a Sunday morning,
那是一个周日的早晨，

104
00:04:08.315 --> 00:04:13.569
when I got a call from the fellow who ran the TV Academy of Arts &amp; Sciences.
我接到了一个管理电视艺术及科学学院朋友的电话。

105
00:04:13.593 --> 00:04:16.562
He was calling me to tell me they had met all day yesterday
他打电话告诉我说，他们昨天谈了一整天，

106
00:04:16.586 --> 00:04:20.799
and he was confidentially telling me they were going to start a hall of fame
他跟我说，告诉你一个秘密，我们将要成立一个名人堂，

107
00:04:20.823 --> 00:04:23.577
and these were the inductees.
然后他告诉我入选者都有谁。

108
00:04:27.021 --> 00:04:28.943
I started to say "Richard Nixon,"
我开头就说“理查德·尼克松”，

109
00:04:28.967 --> 00:04:30.609
because Richard Nixon --
因为理查德·尼克松——

110
00:04:30.633 --> 00:04:32.504
EH: I don't think he was on their list.
艾瑞克：我不认为他在名单上。

111
00:04:32.528 --> 00:04:35.051
NL: William Paley, who started CBS,
诺曼：CBS之父威廉·佩利，

112
00:04:35.075 --> 00:04:38.709
David Sarnoff, who started NBC,
创立NBC的大卫·沙诺夫，

113
00:04:38.733 --> 00:04:39.888
Edward R. Murrow,
爱德华·默罗，

114
00:04:39.912 --> 00:04:43.614
the greatest of the foreign correspondents,
最伟大的驻外记者，

115
00:04:43.638 --> 00:04:44.809
Paddy Chayefsky --
帕迪·查耶夫斯基——

116
00:04:44.833 --> 00:04:47.595
I think the best writer that ever came out of television --
我认为是电视界最好的编剧——

117
00:04:47.619 --> 00:04:49.596
Milton Berle, Lucille Ball
米尔顿·伯利，露西·鲍尔，

118
00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:51.001
and me.
还有我。

119
00:04:51.025 --> 00:04:52.176
EH: Not bad.
艾瑞克：不错。

120
00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:54.915
NL: I call my mother immediately in Hartford, Connecticut.
诺曼：我立刻打电话给在哈特福德，康涅狄格州的妈妈。

121
00:04:54.939 --> 00:04:56.462
"Mom, this is what's happened,
“妈妈，你知道吗，

122
00:04:56.486 --> 00:04:58.085
they're starting a hall of fame."
他们要成立一个名人堂。“

123
00:04:58.109 --> 00:04:59.832
I tell her the list of names and me,
我告诉她那些入选者的名字，还有我，

124
00:04:59.856 --> 00:05:01.014
and she says,
然后她说，

125
00:05:01.038 --> 00:05:03.775
"Listen, if that's what they want to do, who am I to say?"
”听着，如果他们要这么做，我还能说什么？“

126
00:05:03.799 --> 00:05:07.300
(Laughter)
（笑声）

127
00:05:07.324 --> 00:05:10.240
(Applause)
（掌声）

128
00:05:10.264 --> 00:05:11.621
That's my Ma.
这就是我妈妈。

129
00:05:11.645 --> 00:05:13.525
I think it earns that kind of a laugh
我觉得能这么好笑的原因是，

130
00:05:13.549 --> 00:05:15.645
because everybody has a piece of that mother.
因为每个人的妈妈都有这样的一面。

131
00:05:15.669 --> 00:05:16.843
(Laughter)
（笑声）

132
00:05:16.867 --> 00:05:19.724
EH: And the sitcom Jewish mother is born, right there.
艾瑞克：情景喜剧中的犹太人妈妈就这样诞生了。

133
00:05:20.168 --> 00:05:24.978
So your father also played a large role in your life,
你的父亲在你的人生中也扮演了重要的角色，

134
00:05:25.002 --> 00:05:26.652
mostly by his absence.
大部分是因为他的缺席。

135
00:05:26.676 --> 00:05:27.833
NL: Yeah.
诺曼：是。

136
00:05:27.857 --> 00:05:30.480
EH: Tell us what happened when you were nine years old.
艾瑞克：告诉我们你九岁的时候发生了什么。

137
00:05:30.504 --> 00:05:37.478
NL: He was flying to Oklahoma with three guys that my mother said,
诺曼：他当时要与三个人一同飞去俄克拉何马州，我妈妈说，

138
00:05:37.502 --> 00:05:41.161
"I don't want you to have anything to do with them, I don't trust those men."
”我不想你和那三个人有任何关系，我不相信他们。”

139
00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:43.210
That's when I heard,
那时候我听到他说，

140
00:05:43.234 --> 00:05:48.407
maybe not for the first time, "Stifle yourself, Jeanette, I'm going."
“别说了，珍妮特。我要去。” 这大概不是我第一次听到了。

141
00:05:48.431 --> 00:05:49.908
And he went.
然后他去了。

142
00:05:49.932 --> 00:05:54.949
It turns out he was picking up some fake bonds,
结果他拿到了一些假债券，

143
00:05:54.973 --> 00:05:58.496
which he was flying across the country to sell.
飞到全国各地做销售。

144
00:05:59.584 --> 00:06:03.131
But the fact that he was going to Oklahoma in a plane,
但是他坐飞机去俄克拉何马州，

145
00:06:03.155 --> 00:06:06.846
and he was going to bring me back a 10-gallon hat,
他要给我带回一个“十加仑“大檐帽，

146
00:06:06.870 --> 00:06:12.568
just like Ken Maynard, my favorite cowboy wore.
就像我最喜欢的牛仔肯· 梅德纳戴的那样——

147
00:06:13.944 --> 00:06:19.032
You know, this was a few years after Lindbergh crossed the Atlantic.
你知道这是在很多年前林德伯格穿越大西洋之后。

148
00:06:19.056 --> 00:06:22.653
I mean, it was exotic that my father was going there.
我的意思是我爸爸那时候去那儿很奇怪。

149
00:06:22.677 --> 00:06:23.918
But when he came back,
但是当他回来的时候，

150
00:06:23.942 --> 00:06:26.006
they arrested him as he got off the plane.
他一下飞机就被逮捕了。

151
00:06:26.373 --> 00:06:30.769
That night newspapers were all over the house,
那一晚，屋里到处都是报纸，

152
00:06:30.793 --> 00:06:33.413
my father was with his hat in front of his face,
我爸爸戴的帽子遮着他的脸，

153
00:06:33.437 --> 00:06:34.936
manacled to a detective.
他被刑警铐上手铐。

154
00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:39.198
And my mother was selling the furniture, because we were leaving --
我妈妈开始卖家具，因为我们要离开——

155
00:06:39.222 --> 00:06:45.520
she didn't want to stay in that state of shame, in Chelsea, Massachusetts.
她不想待在切尔西，马萨诸塞州生活在耻辱中。

156
00:06:46.348 --> 00:06:50.012
And selling the furniture --
她在卖家具的时候——

157
00:06:50.036 --> 00:06:52.096
the house was loaded with people.
屋里全都是人。

158
00:06:52.532 --> 00:06:54.650
And in the middle of all of that,
在这些人当中，

159
00:06:54.674 --> 00:07:00.862
some strange horse's ass put his hand on my shoulder and said,
有一个奇怪的蠢货把手放到我的肩膀上，说：

160
00:07:00.886 --> 00:07:03.012
"Well, you're the man of the house now."
”嗯，现在你是家中的男人了。“

161
00:07:04.802 --> 00:07:10.373
I'm crying, and this asshole says, "You're the man of the house now."
我正在哭，而这个混蛋说，”现在你是这个家里的男人了。“

162
00:07:11.088 --> 00:07:14.022
And I think that was the moment
我想我就是从那时起

163
00:07:14.046 --> 00:07:18.156
I began to understand the foolishness of the human condition.
开始理解到人性的愚蠢。

164
00:07:19.498 --> 00:07:21.656
So ...
然后……

165
00:07:22.378 --> 00:07:26.958
it took a lot of years to look back at it and feel it was a benefit.
我花了很多年重新审视它并感觉到它的益处。

166
00:07:28.257 --> 00:07:29.407
But --
但是——

167
00:07:29.431 --> 00:07:31.699
EH: It's interesting you call it a benefit.
艾瑞克：你把它看作是有益的这很有趣。

168
00:07:31.723 --> 00:07:34.154
NL: Benefit in that it gave me that springboard.
诺曼：益处在于它给了我一个出发点。

169
00:07:34.178 --> 00:07:37.958
I mean that I could think
我的意思是我可以认为

170
00:07:37.982 --> 00:07:41.170
how foolish it was to say to this crying nine-year-old boy,
对一个在哭泣的九岁男孩说 ”现在你是这个家里的男人了。“

171
00:07:41.194 --> 00:07:43.099
"You're the man of the house now."
这样的行为很愚蠢。

172
00:07:43.123 --> 00:07:46.536
And then I was crying, and then he said,
然后我还在哭，然后他说：

173
00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:48.710
"And men of the house don't cry."
”一家之主是不能流泪的。“

174
00:07:49.575 --> 00:07:51.115
And I ...
然后我……

175
00:07:51.139 --> 00:07:52.424
(Laughter)
（笑声）

176
00:07:52.448 --> 00:07:53.864
So ...
所以……

177
00:07:56.233 --> 00:07:57.740
I look back, and I think
我回顾，然后我想

178
00:07:57.764 --> 00:08:01.907
that's when I learned the foolishness of the human condition,
那个时候，我了解到了人性的愚蠢，

179
00:08:01.931 --> 00:08:04.859
and it's been that gift that I've used.
之后我一直受益于这个礼物。

180
00:08:05.835 --> 00:08:08.363
EH: So you have a father who's absent,
艾瑞克：所以你有一个缺席的父亲，

181
00:08:08.387 --> 00:08:11.333
you have a mother for whom apparently nothing is good enough.
你有一个认为什么都不够好的母亲。

182
00:08:11.690 --> 00:08:16.952
Do you think that starting out as a kid who maybe never felt heard
你觉不觉得，从一个感到从未被倾听的孩子开始，

183
00:08:16.976 --> 00:08:18.498
started you down a journey
一路走來，

184
00:08:18.522 --> 00:08:22.625
that ended with you being an adult with a weekly audience of 120 million people?
这段旅程使你最后成为一个一周拥有一亿两千万收视观众的人？

185
00:08:23.689 --> 00:08:26.699
NL: I love the way you put that question,
诺曼：我喜欢你问这个问题的方式，

186
00:08:26.723 --> 00:08:30.542
because I guess I've spent my life wanting --
因为我猜，我已经花了一生的时间想——

187
00:08:30.566 --> 00:08:32.552
if anything, wanting to be heard.
是否有什么是需要被倾听的。

188
00:08:36.718 --> 00:08:37.972
I think --
我想——

189
00:08:40.344 --> 00:08:41.916
It's a simple answer, yes,
这是个简单的答案，是，

190
00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:44.256
that was what sparked --
就是这个激励了我——

191
00:08:45.677 --> 00:08:47.384
well, there were other things, too.
嗯，也有别的。

192
00:08:47.408 --> 00:08:50.239
When my father was away,
我爸爸不在的时候，

193
00:08:50.263 --> 00:08:56.305
I was fooling with a crystal radio set that we had made together,
我摆弄着一个我们之前一起做的矿石收音机，

194
00:08:56.329 --> 00:09:00.900
and I caught a signal that turned out to be Father Coughlin.
我捕捉到一个信号结果是神父柯林。

195
00:09:01.504 --> 00:09:02.654
(Laughter)
（笑声）

196
00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:05.932
Yeah, somebody laughed.
嗯，一些人笑了。

197
00:09:05.956 --> 00:09:07.383
(Laughter)
（笑声）

198
00:09:07.407 --> 00:09:08.838
But not funny,
但是这并不好笑，

199
00:09:08.862 --> 00:09:10.362
this was a horse's --
这是一个蠢——

200
00:09:10.386 --> 00:09:12.002
another horse's ass --
另一个蠢货——

201
00:09:12.026 --> 00:09:14.617
who was very vocal about hating the New Deal
他激烈地表达对新政，

202
00:09:14.641 --> 00:09:17.104
and Roosevelt and Jews.
对罗斯福，和对犹太人的厌恶。

203
00:09:18.076 --> 00:09:21.409
The first time I ran into an understanding
那是我第一次意识到

204
00:09:21.433 --> 00:09:24.326
that there were people in this world that hated me
这个世界上有人讨厌我

205
00:09:24.350 --> 00:09:26.286
because I was born to Jewish parents.
就因为我父母是犹太人。

206
00:09:27.111 --> 00:09:31.238
And that had an enormous effect on my life.
这对我的人生产生了巨大的影响。

207
00:09:31.879 --> 00:09:33.862
EH: So you had a childhood
艾瑞克：你的童年

208
00:09:33.886 --> 00:09:36.968
with little in the way of strong male role models,
缺少强大的男性榜样，

209
00:09:36.992 --> 00:09:38.528
except for your grandfather.
除了你的爷爷。

210
00:09:39.092 --> 00:09:40.972
Tell us about him.
跟我们说说他。

211
00:09:40.996 --> 00:09:42.146
NL: Oh, my grandfather.
诺曼：哦，我的爷爷。

212
00:09:43.143 --> 00:09:47.604
Well here's the way I always talked about that grandfather.
嗯，我总是这样谈论我的爷爷。

213
00:09:49.426 --> 00:09:50.576
There were parades,
我还是个孩子的时候

214
00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:52.481
lots of parades when I was a kid.
有游行，很多游行。

215
00:09:52.505 --> 00:09:54.417
There were parades on Veteran's Day --
老兵节有游行——

216
00:09:54.441 --> 00:09:56.009
there wasn't a President's Day.
不过总统日没有。

217
00:09:56.033 --> 00:09:57.946
There was Abraham Lincoln's birthday,
亚伯拉罕·林肯的生日有，

218
00:09:57.970 --> 00:10:00.074
George Washington's birthday
乔治·华盛顿的生日有，

219
00:10:00.098 --> 00:10:02.588
and Flag Day ...
还有国旗日……

220
00:10:03.641 --> 00:10:05.400
And lots of little parades.
也有很多小游行。

221
00:10:05.424 --> 00:10:06.853
My grandfather used to take me
我爷爷以前会带我去，

222
00:10:06.877 --> 00:10:08.603
and we'd stand on the street corner,
我们会站在街角，

223
00:10:08.627 --> 00:10:09.963
he'd hold my hand,
他拉着我的手，

224
00:10:09.987 --> 00:10:13.050
and I'd look up and I'd see a tear running down his eye.
我抬头会看到他流眼泪。

225
00:10:15.730 --> 00:10:18.094
And he meant a great deal to me.
他对我来说意味着很多。

226
00:10:18.118 --> 00:10:23.476
And he used to write presidents of the United States.
他以前会给美国总统写信。

227
00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.120
Every letter started,
每封信都这样开始，

228
00:10:25.144 --> 00:10:28.223
"My dearest, darling Mr. President,"
”我最最亲爱的总统先生，“

229
00:10:28.247 --> 00:10:32.865
and he'd tell him something wonderful about what he did.
然后告诉他一些他做的了不起的事。

230
00:10:32.889 --> 00:10:35.821
But when he disagreed with the President, he also wrote,
但是当他不同意总统的决定时，他也写信。

231
00:10:35.845 --> 00:10:37.512
"My dearest, darling Mr. President,
”我最最亲爱的总统先生，

232
00:10:37.536 --> 00:10:39.330
Didn't I tell you last week ...?"
上星期我是不是跟你说过……？”

233
00:10:39.354 --> 00:10:40.933
(Laughter)
（笑声）

234
00:10:41.379 --> 00:10:46.559
And I would run down the stairs every now and then
我经常往楼下跑，

235
00:10:46.583 --> 00:10:47.815
and pick up the mail.
去拿信件。

236
00:10:47.839 --> 00:10:49.058
We were three flights up,
我们当时住在康涅狄格州纽黑文约克街的74号，

237
00:10:49.082 --> 00:10:51.307
74 York Street, New Haven, Connecticut.
要上三段楼梯。

238
00:10:52.765 --> 00:10:59.377
And I'd pick up a little white envelope reading, "Shya C. called at this address."
我会拿到一个小信封，上面写着 “住在这里的Shya C.”。

239
00:11:02.554 --> 00:11:07.090
And that's the story I have told about my grandfather --
这就是我讲述过的关于我爷爷的故事。

240
00:11:07.114 --> 00:11:09.135
EH: They wrote him back on the envelopes --
艾瑞克：他们在信封上回信——

241
00:11:09.159 --> 00:11:10.379
NL: They wrote back.
诺曼：他们回信了。

242
00:11:12.682 --> 00:11:17.088
But I have shown them myself,
但我已经向他们坦白，

243
00:11:17.112 --> 00:11:22.230
going way back to Phil Donahue and others before him,
从多年前的菲尔多纳休 还有在他之前的其他人，

244
00:11:22.254 --> 00:11:26.563
literally dozens of interviews in which I told that story.
几乎每次的访谈中，我都有提到那个故事，

245
00:11:28.103 --> 00:11:33.222
This will be the second time I have said the whole story was a lie.
这将是我第二次说这个故事是个谎言。

246
00:11:35.971 --> 00:11:40.163
The truth was my grandfather took me to parades,
真相是我爷爷带我去游行，

247
00:11:40.187 --> 00:11:41.510
we had lots of those.
我们去过很多次。

248
00:11:41.914 --> 00:11:44.294
The truth is a tear came down his eye.
真相是他流泪了。

249
00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:48.867
The truth is he would write an occasional letter,
真相是他偶尔会写一封信，

250
00:11:48.891 --> 00:11:51.294
and I did pick up those little envelopes.
而我的确拿到了那些小信封。

251
00:11:52.356 --> 00:11:55.768
But "My dearest darling Mr. President,"
但是“我最最亲爱的总统先生”，

252
00:11:55.792 --> 00:11:58.254
all the rest of it,
和剩下的所有

253
00:11:58.278 --> 00:12:02.794
is a story I borrowed from a good friend
都是一个我从好朋友那儿借鉴的故事，

254
00:12:02.818 --> 00:12:08.328
whose grandfather was that grandfather who wrote those letters.
他的爷爷才是那个写了那些信的爷爷。

255
00:12:10.326 --> 00:12:16.771
And, I mean, I stole Arthur Marshall's grandfather
我是说，我偷了阿瑟·马歇尔的爷爷，

256
00:12:16.795 --> 00:12:18.525
and made him my own.
把他变成了我自己的。

257
00:12:20.817 --> 00:12:21.967
Always.
一直都是这样。

258
00:12:21.991 --> 00:12:24.605
When I started to write my memoir --
当我开始写我的回忆录时——

259
00:12:24.629 --> 00:12:26.081
"Even this --"
《甚至这些——》

260
00:12:26.105 --> 00:12:27.270
How about that?
你怎么看这件事？

261
00:12:27.294 --> 00:12:29.525
"Even This I Get to Experience."
甚至这些我都曾经历过

262
00:12:30.668 --> 00:12:32.419
When I started to write the memoir
当我开始写回忆录时，

263
00:12:32.443 --> 00:12:34.002
and I started to think about it,
我开始思考，

264
00:12:34.026 --> 00:12:35.176
and then I --
然后我——

265
00:12:36.095 --> 00:12:37.245
I --
我——

266
00:12:38.349 --> 00:12:42.151
I did a reasonable amount of crying,
我真情流露地哭了，

267
00:12:42.175 --> 00:12:46.008
and I realized how much I needed the father.
然后我意识到我是多么地需要“父亲”。

268
00:12:46.959 --> 00:12:50.260
So much so that I appropriated Arthur Marshall's grandfather.
这么需要以至于我借用了阿瑟·马歇尔的爷爷。

269
00:12:51.395 --> 00:12:53.832
So much so, the word "father" --
这么需要“爸爸”——

270
00:12:54.393 --> 00:12:56.338
I have six kids by the way.
顺便一提，我有六个孩子，

271
00:12:57.093 --> 00:12:58.800
My favorite role in life.
“爸爸”是我生活中最喜欢的角色，

272
00:13:01.302 --> 00:13:03.778
It and husband to my wife Lyn.
还有身为我妻子，林，的丈夫这个角色。

273
00:13:07.792 --> 00:13:12.273
But I stole the man's identity because I needed the father.
但是我偷用了那个人的身份因为我需要一个“爸爸“。

274
00:13:13.063 --> 00:13:16.746
Now I've gone through a whole lot of shit
我经历了那么多悲惨的事，

275
00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:18.777
and come out on the other side,
结果我站到了另一边，

276
00:13:18.801 --> 00:13:20.388
and I forgive my father --
我原谅了我的爸爸——

277
00:13:20.412 --> 00:13:21.622
the best thing I --
最好的事情——

278
00:13:21.646 --> 00:13:22.935
the worst thing I --
最坏的事情——

279
00:13:23.531 --> 00:13:26.615
The word I'd like to use about him and think about him is --
我想起他，形容他想要用的词是——

280
00:13:26.639 --> 00:13:28.007
he was a rascal.
他是一个混蛋。

281
00:13:28.840 --> 00:13:33.753
The fact that he lied and stole and cheated
他说谎，偷窃，欺骗，

282
00:13:33.777 --> 00:13:34.977
and went to prison ...
然后进了监狱……

283
00:13:37.169 --> 00:13:41.026
I submerge that in the word "rascal."
我让这些都沉浸在“混蛋”这个词中。

284
00:13:41.629 --> 00:13:47.756
EH: Well there's a saying that amateurs borrow and professionals steal.
艾瑞克：人们常说，"外行借，内行偷"。

285
00:13:48.186 --> 00:13:49.411
NL: I'm a pro.
诺曼：我是职业的。

286
00:13:49.435 --> 00:13:50.586
EH: You're a pro.
艾瑞克：没错，你是职业的。

287
00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:51.926
(Laughter)
（笑声）

288
00:13:51.950 --> 00:13:55.097
And that quote is widely attributed to John Lennon,
人们普遍认为这句话出自约翰·列侬，

289
00:13:55.121 --> 00:13:57.311
but it turns out he stole it from T.S. Eliot.
但其实他是从艾略特那偷来的。

290
00:13:57.335 --> 00:13:58.724
So you're in good company.
所以你有好同伴了。

291
00:13:58.748 --> 00:13:59.906
(Laughter)
（笑声）

292
00:14:02.422 --> 00:14:04.747
EH: I want to talk about your work.
艾瑞克：我想谈谈你的成就。

293
00:14:04.771 --> 00:14:07.477
Obviously the impact of your work has been written about
显然你的成就所带来的影响已经被评论过，

294
00:14:07.501 --> 00:14:09.867
and I'm sure you've heard about it all your life:
我相信你已经听过很多：

295
00:14:09.891 --> 00:14:11.042
what it meant to people,
它对人们意味着什么，

296
00:14:11.066 --> 00:14:12.496
what it meant to our culture,
它对我们的文化意味着什么，

297
00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:15.521
you heard the applause when I just named the names of the shows,
当我刚才列举那些电视剧电影的时候你听到了掌声，

298
00:14:15.545 --> 00:14:18.973
you raised half the people in the room through your work.
你使这里半数的人起身致敬你的成就。

299
00:14:18.997 --> 00:14:22.532
But have there ever been any stories about the impact of your work
有没有过什么关于你成就影响的故事

300
00:14:22.556 --> 00:14:23.870
that surprised you?
使你感到惊讶呢？

301
00:14:24.560 --> 00:14:25.774
NL: Oh, god --
诺曼：哦，上帝——

302
00:14:26.207 --> 00:14:31.099
surprised me and delighted me from head to toe.
使我整个人都感到惊讶和欣喜。

303
00:14:33.257 --> 00:14:38.750
There was "An Evening with Norman Lear" within the last year
去年有一个和诺曼·李尔的夜晚的谈话节目，

304
00:14:38.774 --> 00:14:42.278
that a group of hip-hop impresarios,
把一群嘻哈经理人，

305
00:14:42.302 --> 00:14:46.238
performers and the Academy put together.
舞者和电视学会聚在一起。

306
00:14:47.722 --> 00:14:49.626
The subtext of "An Evening with ..."
“和……的夜晚”的潜台词是：

307
00:14:49.650 --> 00:14:53.739
was: What do a 92-year-old Jew --
一个92岁的犹太人——

308
00:14:53.763 --> 00:14:54.914
then 92 --
已经92岁了——

309
00:14:54.938 --> 00:14:56.951
and the world of hip-hop have in common?
和嘻哈界有什么共同点？

310
00:14:56.975 --> 00:14:59.664
Russell Simmons was among seven on the stage.
拉塞尔·西蒙斯是台上的七人之一。

311
00:15:00.603 --> 00:15:04.924
And when he talked about the shows,
当他谈到那些电视剧时，

312
00:15:04.948 --> 00:15:09.481
he wasn't talking about the Hollywood,
他不是在谈论好莱坞

313
00:15:09.505 --> 00:15:13.229
George Jefferson in "The Jeffersons,"
《杰佛逊一家》中的乔治·杰佛逊

314
00:15:13.253 --> 00:15:15.668
or the show that was a number five show.
或是这个当时排名第五的电视剧。

315
00:15:16.667 --> 00:15:22.318
He was talking about a simple thing that made a big --
他在谈论的是，一件简单的事情产生了巨大的——

316
00:15:25.144 --> 00:15:26.345
EH: Impact on him?
艾瑞克：对他产生了巨大的影响？

317
00:15:26.369 --> 00:15:28.307
NL: An impact on him --
诺曼：对他的影响——

318
00:15:28.331 --> 00:15:30.838
I was hesitating over the word, "change."
我在犹豫用“改变”这个词。

319
00:15:31.250 --> 00:15:33.813
It's hard for me to imagine,
我很难想象，

320
00:15:33.837 --> 00:15:35.665
you know, changing somebody's life,
你知道，改变某人的人生，

321
00:15:35.689 --> 00:15:37.474
but that's the way he put it.
但是他是这么说的。

322
00:15:37.498 --> 00:15:43.587
He saw George Jefferson write a check on "The Jeffersons,"
他看到乔治·杰佛逊在《杰佛逊一家》中开了一张支票，

323
00:15:43.611 --> 00:15:47.221
and he never knew that a black man could write a check.
而他从不知道一个黑人可以写支票。

324
00:15:48.608 --> 00:15:53.561
And he says it just impacted his life so --
他说，这影响了他的人生——

325
00:15:53.585 --> 00:15:55.270
it changed his life.
这改变了他的人生。

326
00:15:55.294 --> 00:15:58.768
And when I hear things like that --
而当我听到这样的事情时——

327
00:15:58.792 --> 00:16:00.467
little things --
这些微不足道的小事——

328
00:16:00.491 --> 00:16:03.673
because I know that there isn't anybody in this audience
因为我知道这里的观众没有人

329
00:16:03.697 --> 00:16:10.200
that wasn't likely responsible today for some little thing they did for somebody,
会在意他们为别人做过的小事。

330
00:16:10.224 --> 00:16:15.566
whether it's as little as a smile or an unexpected "Hello,"
不管它小到是一个微笑还是一个意想不到的“你好”，

331
00:16:15.590 --> 00:16:17.954
that's how little this thing was.
那件事就是这么小。

332
00:16:18.653 --> 00:16:22.924
It could have been the dresser of the set
有可能是梳妆者

333
00:16:22.948 --> 00:16:24.634
who put the checkbook on the thing,
把支票簿放在了那上面，

334
00:16:24.658 --> 00:16:28.347
and George had nothing to do while he was speaking, so he wrote it,
而乔治在说话的时候无事可做便写了支票，

335
00:16:28.371 --> 00:16:29.647
I don't know.
我不知道，

336
00:16:29.671 --> 00:16:30.821
But --
但是——

337
00:16:31.454 --> 00:16:34.392
EH: So in addition to the long list I shared in the beginning,
艾瑞克：所以除了我在一开始提到的那些成就，

338
00:16:34.416 --> 00:16:37.062
I should have also mentioned that you invented hip-hop.
我也应该提及说是你创造了嘻哈。

339
00:16:37.086 --> 00:16:38.187
(Laughter)
（笑声）

340
00:16:38.211 --> 00:16:39.654
NL: Well ...
诺曼：额……

341
00:16:40.575 --> 00:16:42.060
EH: I want to talk about --
艾瑞克：我想谈谈——

342
00:16:42.084 --> 00:16:43.384
NL: Well, then do it.
诺曼：嗯，那就加上吧。

343
00:16:43.408 --> 00:16:48.218
(Laughter)
（笑声）

344
00:16:49.526 --> 00:16:52.288
EH: You've lead a life of accomplishment,
艾瑞克：你走过了充满成就的一生，

345
00:16:52.312 --> 00:16:54.248
but you've also built a life of meaning.
但同时你也造就了充满意义的一生。

346
00:16:54.629 --> 00:16:57.201
And all of us strive to do both of those things --
我们所有人都在努力达成这两件事——

347
00:16:57.225 --> 00:16:58.819
not all of us manage to.
不是所有人都能成功。

348
00:16:59.804 --> 00:17:03.575
But even those of us who do manage to accomplish both of those,
但即使是那些成功达成这两件事的人，

349
00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:06.169
very rarely do we figure out how to do them together.
也极少能弄明白如何同时达成它们。

350
00:17:06.704 --> 00:17:11.584
You managed to push culture forward through your art
你成功用艺术推动了文化的前行，

351
00:17:11.608 --> 00:17:15.466
while also achieving world-beating commercial success.
同时也取得了惊人的商业成就。

352
00:17:15.490 --> 00:17:16.680
How did you do both?
你是如何同时做到的？

353
00:17:23.211 --> 00:17:29.027
NL: Here's where my mind goes when I hear that recitation of all I accomplished.
诺曼：这是我在听到我所有的成就时想到的。

354
00:17:31.124 --> 00:17:35.180
This planet is one of a billion,
这里是无数行星中的一颗，

355
00:17:35.204 --> 00:17:36.393
they tell us,
他们告诉我们，

356
00:17:36.695 --> 00:17:42.513
in a universe of which there are billions --
在这个宇宙中有几十亿——

357
00:17:42.537 --> 00:17:44.105
billions of universes,
几十亿个宇宙，

358
00:17:44.129 --> 00:17:47.736
billions of planets ...
几十亿颗行星……

359
00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:49.643
which we're trying to save
我们在试图保护，

360
00:17:49.667 --> 00:17:51.451
and it requires saving.
它也需要我们的保护。

361
00:17:53.369 --> 00:17:54.543
But ...
但是……

362
00:17:55.519 --> 00:17:59.169
anything I may have accomplished is --
我的任何成就——

363
00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:03.629
my sister once asked me what she does about something
我姐姐曾问我，对于在纽因顿，康涅狄格州发生的事情，

364
00:18:03.653 --> 00:18:06.595
that was going on in Newington, Connecticut.
她做了些什么。

365
00:18:06.619 --> 00:18:09.544
And I said, "Write your alderman or your mayor or something."
我说：“写信给市议员或者市长或者别的什么。”

366
00:18:09.568 --> 00:18:12.706
She said, "Well I'm not Norman Lear, I'm Claire Lear."
她说：“额，我不是诺曼·李尔，我是克莱尔·李尔。”

367
00:18:13.639 --> 00:18:18.155
And that was the first time I said what I'm saying,
然后那是我第一次说到我现正在谈的这些东西，

368
00:18:18.179 --> 00:18:22.518
I said, "Claire. With everything you think about what I may have done
我说：“克莱尔，你认为我做过的所有事

369
00:18:22.542 --> 00:18:24.019
and everything you've done," --
和你做过的所有事，”——

370
00:18:24.043 --> 00:18:26.386
she never left Newington --
她从未离开过纽因顿——

371
00:18:26.410 --> 00:18:28.220
"can you get your fingers close enough
“当你考虑到地球宇宙等等这些大小的时候，

372
00:18:28.244 --> 00:18:32.161
when you consider the size of the planet and so forth,
你即使把手指努力并拢，那缝隙也不足以

373
00:18:32.185 --> 00:18:35.399
to measure anything I may have done to anything you may have done?"
衡量我做过的或者是你做过的事吗。“

374
00:18:35.970 --> 00:18:37.200
So ...
所以……

375
00:18:38.306 --> 00:18:41.894
I am convinced we're all responsible
我相信我们都能

376
00:18:41.918 --> 00:18:45.139
for doing as much as I may have accomplished.
做到我也许达成了的。

377
00:18:47.089 --> 00:18:48.979
And I understand what you're saying --
我理解你说的是什么——

378
00:18:49.003 --> 00:18:50.718
EH: It's an articulate deflection --
艾瑞克：这是一个很明显的谎言——

379
00:18:50.742 --> 00:18:56.678
NL: But you have to really buy into the size and scope of the creator's enterprise, here.
诺曼：但是你必须考虑到造物主造就的空间和大小，在这里。

380
00:18:56.702 --> 00:18:59.286
EH: But here on this planet you have really mattered.
艾瑞克：但是在这里在地球上，你真的很重要。

381
00:18:59.310 --> 00:19:00.460
NL: I'm a son of a gun.
诺曼：我是个混蛋。

382
00:19:00.801 --> 00:19:02.322
(Laughter)
（笑声）

383
00:19:02.346 --> 00:19:06.144
EH: So I have one more question for you.
艾瑞克：我还有一个问题。

384
00:19:06.168 --> 00:19:07.441
How old do you feel?
你觉得自己几岁了？

385
00:19:09.231 --> 00:19:13.643
NL: I am the peer of whoever I'm talking to.
诺曼：我是任何和我交谈者的同龄人。

386
00:19:14.524 --> 00:19:15.896
EH: Well, I feel 93.
艾瑞克：嗯，我觉得我93岁了。

387
00:19:15.920 --> 00:19:22.480
(Applause)
（掌声）

388
00:19:22.504 --> 00:19:23.814
NL: We out of here?
诺曼：结束了？

389
00:19:23.838 --> 00:19:25.722
EH: Well, I feel 93 years old,
艾瑞克：嗯，我觉得我93岁了，

390
00:19:25.746 --> 00:19:29.535
but I hope to one day feel as young as the person I'm sitting across from.
但是我希望有一天，我也能感觉和坐在我对面的这个人一样年轻。

391
00:19:29.559 --> 00:19:30.709
Ladies and gentlemen,
女士们先生们，

392
00:19:30.733 --> 00:19:32.157
the incomparable Norman Lear.
致敬伟大的诺曼·李尔。

393
00:19:32.181 --> 00:19:37.845
(Applause)
（掌声）

394
00:19:37.869 --> 00:19:39.020
NL: Thank you.
诺曼：谢谢。

395
00:19:39.044 --> 00:19:44.985
(Applause)
（掌声）